Consider these struct definitions: struct RefCounted<T> { counter: usize, data: T,
} struct Foo<U> { field: u32, data: U
} and now assume that I have a *const RefCounted<Foo<u32>> which is coerced: let pointer1: *const RefCounted<Foo<u32>> = ...;
let pointer2: *const RefCounted<Foo<dyn Debug>> = pointer1; If I now try to get the address of the field field... let pointer3: *const u32 = unsafe { raw_addr!((*pointer2).data.field) }; ...this operation requires valid metadata. This is because the offset of field is a function of the alignment of Foo<U>, which is a function of the alignment of U. In these cases, the compiler will load the alignment from the vtable and do the required address computations itself.

